.TH _PRINTF 3 "March 2026" "2.0" "_printf manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- printf clone

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function is a simplified version of the standard C
.B printf
function. It writes the output to the standard output (stdout) according to the format string and the additional arguments provided.

The function supports a limited set of conversion specifiers and flags.

The format string may contain ordinary characters (which are printed as-is) and format specifiers starting with the '%' character.

.SH FORMAT SPECIFIERS
The following conversion specifiers are supported:
.TP
.B %c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Prints a null-terminated string.
.TP
.B %d
Prints a signed integer in decimal notation.
.TP
.B %i
Same as 'd', prints a signed integer in decimal notation.
.TP
.B %%
Prints a literal '%' character.
.TP
.B Any other character
When an undefined specifier is encountered, it is printed as-is, including the leading '%'.

.SH FLAGS
The following flags can be used with the conversion specifiers:
.TP
.B +
Prefix a positive number with a plus sign.
.TP
.B -
Left-justify the output within the given field width.
.TP
.B 0
Pad the output with leading zeros instead of spaces.
.TP
.B (space)
Prefix a positive number with a space.
.TP
.B Width
A decimal integer that specifies the minimum field width.

Note: Precision and length modifiers are not supported in this implementation.

.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon successful completion, the number of characters printed is returned. If an error occurs, such as a null format string, the function returns -1.

.SH EXAMPLES
Greet the world:
_printf("Hello, World!\n")
Output: "Hello, World!"

Print a character:
_printf("Character: %c\n", 'A')
Output: "Character: A"

Print a string:
_printf("String: %s\n", "example")
Output: "String: example"

Print integers:
_printf("Integer: %d, %i\n", 42, -42)
Output: "Integer: 42, -42"

Print a percent sign:
_printf("Percent sign: %%\n")
Output: "Percent sign: %"

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR printf (3)

